I'm not sure if this is a breathe problem or a doxygen one.

When the Doxyfile sets `INLINE_INHERITED_MEMBERS` to `YES`, each time a base class member is documented within a subclass it has the same link target. This leads to warnings from Sphinx e.g.
```
Warning: Duplicate target detected: classBase_1a641e04b3c65c74e058e21a37ae805f98

/home/bmerry/work/sdp/bugs/breathe-dup-ids/doc/index.rst:7: WARNING: Duplicate ID: "classBase_1a641e04b3c65c74e058e21a37ae805f98".
/home/bmerry/work/sdp/bugs/breathe-dup-ids/doc/index.rst:7: WARNING: Duplicate explicit target name: "classBase_1a641e04b3c65c74e058e21a37ae805f98".
```

Example code:
```c++
/**
 * @file
 */

/// Base class
class Base
{
public:
    /// Base-class member function
    void foo();
};

/// Class A
class A : public Base {};
/// Class B
class B : public Base {};
```

I'm using doxygen 1.8.11, breathe 4.7.3, Sphinx 1.6.4, Python 2.7.12. The Doxyfile is a default-generated one, just with `INLINE_INHERITED_MEMBERS` changed to `YES`.

is there anyway to tell the echo to "talk" outside of forcing it in the function return?

@ask.intent("SleepIntent")
def sleepy_time():
    os.system("rundll32.exe powrprof.dll,SetSuspendState 0,1,0")
    msg = render_template('sleep')
    return statement(msg) 

See the above function. what is happening here (when I call this function) is the machine is instantly falling asleep, and its never making it to the end of the function to read the string in, and therefore never triggers the return.

what i tried doing was breaking it out into two functions, so the sleep function calls the sleep talk function. I wanted to call it, have the verbal response go through the echo, then jump back to the calling function and continue on with the sleep, but this doesnt work. If I enter in debug statements, I can see that the sleep function, does call sleep talk function, but still nothing is heard prior to the sleep.

def sleepy_time_talk():
    msg = render_template('sleep')
    return statement(msg) 

@ask.intent("SleepIntent")
def sleepy_time():
    sleepy_time_talk()
    os.system("rundll32.exe powrprof.dll,SetSuspendState 0,1,0")

Namespaces are definitely a needed feature, as is an easier way to add attributes to tags. I propose this be done in the following way:

```python
from dicttoxml import dicttoxml

dict = {
    "Envelope": {
        "_ns":    "soapenv",
        "_attrs": {
            "soapenv": { "_ns": "xmlns", "value": "http://schemas.xmlsoap.org/soap/envelope/" },
            "urn": { "_ns": "xmlns", "value": "urn:partner.soap.sforce.com" },
            "otherExample": "test value"
        },
        "Header": {
            "_ns":    "soapenv",
            "SessionHeader": {
                "_ns": "urn",
                "sessionId": "3MVG9uudbyLbNPZMtuxO54qpe.DK5jaS6q_pb7mBcusBAzQcItE_a2ZZoOSucuDuYqLgWgFd6iHKr6GUAWjWx"
            }
        },
        "Body": {
            "_ns": "soapenv",
            "query": {
                "_ns": "urn",
                "queryString": {
                    "_ns": "urn",
                    "text": "SELECT Id, Name FROM Account LIMIT 2"
                } 
            }
        }
    }
}

myXml = dicttoxml(dict, root=False, attrType=False)
print(myXml)
```

Which would return the following XML structure:

```xml
<soapenv:Envelope xmlns:soapenv="http://schemas.xmlsoap.org/soap/envelope/"
   xmlns:urn="partner.soap.sforce.com" otherExample="test value">
  <soapenv:Header>
     <urn:SessionHeader
    <urn:sessionId>3MVG9uudbyLbNPZMtuxO54qpe.DK5jaS6q_pb7mBcusBAzQcItE_a2ZZoOSucuDuYqLgWgFd6iHKr6GUAWjWx</urn:sessionId>
     </urn:SessionHeader>
  </soapenv:Header>
  <soapenv:Body>
     <urn:query>
        <urn:queryString>SELECT Id, Name FROM Account LIMIT 2</urn:queryString>
     </urn:query>
  </soapenv:Body>
</soapenv:Envelope>
```

I could take a crack at implementing this myself, but I am by no means a great python developer yet. This is just a feature I feel is sorely needed and would put this library ahead of all the rest. Thanks!

